The article reports on several positive economic indicators in the United States. The jobs report for January shows the addition of 200,000 new jobs, exceeding economists' expectations. Wages also rose at the fastest pace since the recession in 2009. The Employment Cost Index shows that workers had their best year for pay gains in 2017 since before the financial crisis. A survey of business economists revealed that more companies are increasing wages and salaries than at any time in the past 18 years. Manufacturing in the US is expanding at a strong pace, benefiting from consumer spending and business investment. Jobless claims remain near a 45-year low. The S&P 500's gain in January suggests a positive outlook for the rest of the year, based on historical trends. Consumer confidence also increased in January, driven by higher expectations about the economy. Lastly, US oil production hit 10 million barrels per day for the first time since 1970, largely due to the boom in shale oil and natural gas.